          "create_time": 1704067200,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Help me draft an artist statement for a 2024 solo show. My practice explores public-art interventions and sculpture."
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "msg2": {
        "id": "msg2",
        "parent": "msg1",
        "children": [
          "msg3"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "assistant"
          },
          "create_time": 1704067300,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Here's a starting draft. Working across photography, sculpture, and site-specific installation, your practice asks how public art reshapes everyday urban encounters..."
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "msg3": {
        "id": "msg3",
        "parent": "msg2",
        "children": [
          "msg4"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "user"
          },
          "create_time": 1704067500,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Make it shorter — two paragraphs max, and lean into the word 'intervention'."
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "msg4": {
        "id": "msg4",
        "parent": "msg3",
        "children": [],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "assistant"
          },
          "create_time": 1704067700,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Intervention is the verb at the center of my practice. I put sculpture and image where people do not expect it — on billboards, in storefronts, at the edge of a city block — and I watch what happens when the public encounters it mid-routine.\n\nThe work sits between gallery and street, asking whether art belongs to institutions or to the cities that host it."
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "title": "Real estate — ADU permit timeline",
    "create_time": 1706745600,
    "update_time": 1706746400,
    "current_node": "m4",
    "mapping": {
      "root": {
        "id": "root",
        "parent": null,
        "children": [
          "m1"
        ],
        "message": null
      },
      "m1": {
        "id": "m1",
        "parent": "root",
        "children": [
          "m2"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "user"
          },
          "create_time": 1706745600,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "What's a typical permit timeline for an ADU in California?"
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "m2": {
        "id": "m2",
        "parent": "m1",
        "children": [
          "m3"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "assistant"
          },
          "create_time": 1706745800,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "ADU permit timelines in California vary by jurisdiction but generally take 60 to 120 days for ministerial review, followed by a construction loan draw schedule that aligns with inspections."
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "m3": {
        "id": "m3",
        "parent": "m2",
        "children": [
          "m4"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "user"
          },
          "create_time": 1706746000,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "What about mortgage / construction loan structure for someone building on their own land?"
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "m4": {
        "id": "m4",
        "parent": "m3",
        "children": [],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "assistant"
          },
          "create_time": 1706746200,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Construction-to-permanent loans are the common structure. The lender disburses in stages tied to inspection milestones (foundation, framing, final), then converts the total to a permanent mortgage once occupancy is signed off."
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "title": "Portfolio rebalance — Q2 review",
    "create_time": 1712016000,
    "update_time": 1712016800,
    "current_node": "a4",
    "mapping": {
      "root": {
        "id": "root",
        "parent": null,
        "children": [
          "a1"
        ],
        "message": null
      },
      "a1": {
        "id": "a1",
        "parent": "root",
        "children": [
          "a2"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "user"
          },
          "create_time": 1712016000,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "How should I think about rebalancing a diversified portfolio quarterly?"
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "a2": {
        "id": "a2",
        "parent": "a1",
        "children": [
          "a3"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "assistant"
          },
          "create_time": 1712016200,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Quarterly rebalancing has two common rules: threshold-based (rebalance when an allocation drifts 5 percent from target) and calendar-based (rebalance on a fixed date regardless of drift). Threshold-based tends to outperform in volatile markets."
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "a3": {
        "id": "a3",
        "parent": "a2",
        "children": [
          "a4"
        ],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "user"
          },
          "create_time": 1712016400,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "What about tax-loss harvesting — when in the cycle is best?"
            ]
          }
        }
      },
      "a4": {
        "id": "a4",
        "parent": "a3",
        "children": [],
        "message": {
          "author": {
            "role": "assistant"
          },
          "create_time": 1712016600,
          "content": {
            "parts": [
              "Late November through mid-December is the conventional window. Harvest losses before year-end, mind the wash sale rule (30 days), and replace with a similar-but-not-identical ETF to keep your exposure."
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
